    "kernel": "6.17.0-1012-oem",
    "notes": "Need for Speed Heat is not reliably playable for me under Proton right now. It\n  started as a black screen after the EA App/Link2EA launch, and the logs\n  repeatedly pointed to the EA in-game overlay with messages about Steam\n  injection failure, forced load, and the overlay forcing the resolution down to\n  1 x 1. After disabling the EA overlay pieces inside the prefix, the game\n  improved a lot and could sometimes get through the intro, reach the menu, and\n  even start solo play, but it still freezes inconsistently, sometimes at the\n  intro, sometimes on the loading screen, and sometimes before startup fully\n  completes. I also reset the display profile, cleared shader cache, rebuilt the\n  Proton prefix, switched between Proton Experimental and GE-Proton, and tested\n  with PROTON_NO_ESYNC=1 PROTON_NO_FSYNC=1, but the result is still unstable.\n  One extra complication is that EA cloud sync kept restoring the same older\n  save/profile, so save-state interference may still be part of the problem.\n  Overall, the main issue seems to be EA App / overlay / cloud-sync interaction\n  under Proton rather than simple GPU detection or a basic launch failure.",
